         <abstract>
            <p>Warrants often expire with the price of the common below the exercise price whereas, given more time, the common might have risen above the exercise price, resulting in a tangible value for the warrant. Because the investor is less likely to be able to exercise a warrant profitably, the shorter its time to expiration, one might expect warrant values to increase as time to expiration increases, other things equal. The author's investigation of actual price behavior confirms this expectation and suggests a method for valuing warrants that takes time to expiration into account.</p>
          </abstract>
